# =============================================================================
# .env-custom — PERSISTENT OPERATOR OVERRIDES (safe to edit by hand)
# =============================================================================
#
# WHAT THIS FILE IS FOR
#   This is the place to put environment overrides that must SURVIVE every
#   `ansiblew` run. The sibling `.env` file is fully regenerated on every run
#   from inventory and MUST NOT be hand-edited — your edits there are lost.
#   This file is the opposite: Ansible creates it ONCE and NEVER overwrites it
#   (the generating task uses `force: no`), so anything you set here persists.
#
# HOW THE OVERRIDE WORKS
#   Docker Compose is told (via the COMPOSE_ENV_FILES variable, wired in the
#   la-compose role) to load BOTH files in order:
#       COMPOSE_ENV_FILES=.env,.env-custom
#   When the same key appears in both, the LAST file wins — so any key you set
#   here overrides the generated value in `.env`. Requires Docker Compose
#   >= v2.24. Ansible-driven deploys set COMPOSE_ENV_FILES automatically; if you
#   run `docker compose` by hand, export it yourself:
#       export COMPOSE_ENV_FILES=.env,.env-custom
#
# NOTES
#   - Keep this file out of version control (it may hold secrets).
#   - Only override what you need; leave the rest to the generated `.env`.
#   - This does NOT change application config files under /data/<svc>/config/;
#     for those use the per-service local-config files (see docs/configuration.md).
#
# EXAMPLES (uncomment and adjust):
#   # Bump a service's JVM heap (see <SERVICE>_JAVA_OPTS in .env for the full string):
#   # COLLECTORY_MAX_MEMORY=4g
#   # Override a generated password without touching inventory:
#   # MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=my-persistent-secret
#   # Pin which compose profiles start by default:
#   # COMPOSE_PROFILES=app-core
# =============================================================================
